<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How is child support calculated?", answer: "About 40 US states use the income shares model: combine both parents' incomes, find the percentage of combined income that the child(ren) would 'cost' based on state schedules (typically 17% for one child, 25% for two, 29% for three), and divide the total support obligation between the parents proportional to their income share. The non-custodial parent pays the custodial parent. The other 10 states use the percentage-of-income model (a flat percentage of the non-custodial parent's income only) or a hybrid Melson formula." },
  { question: "Who pays child support?", answer: "In most cases, the non-custodial parent (the one with less parenting time) pays the custodial parent. In joint custody arrangements where both parents have roughly equal parenting time, the higher-earning parent typically pays the lower-earning parent based on income disparity. Child support is for the children's expenses — it's not optional and it's not negotiable down based on the recipient's spending habits, though in extreme cases courts can intervene." },
  { question: "How long does child support last?", answer: "In most US states, until the child turns 18 (or 19 if still in high school). A few states extend it through college: New York to 21, Massachusetts to 23 if the child is enrolled in college, Illinois has discretionary college support. Most states do not require parents to pay for college. Special needs children may be entitled to lifetime support. Child support generally ends automatically when the child reaches the age of majority — no court order needed." },
  { question: "Can child support be modified?", answer: "Yes — most states allow modification when there's a substantial change in circumstances: job loss, significant income change (typically 15%+ either way), change in custody arrangement, or change in the child's needs. Modifications require going back to court. Some states have automatic review every 3 years. Voluntary income reductions (taking a lower-paying job) typically don't qualify and can result in 'imputed income' calculations based on what you should be earning." },
  { question: "Does child support cover everything?", answer: "No — base child support typically covers food, shelter, clothing, and transportation. Things often calculated separately or as add-ons: health insurance premiums, uninsured medical expenses, childcare for working parents, extracurricular activities, private school tuition, and college expenses. Most states require both parents to contribute to these add-ons proportional to income, on top of base support. The calculator estimates only base support — actual orders include more line items." }
]) %>

